         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">3/10/81 ¶  ¶ Allow me to ask you, dear Mr Hemsley, whether in the progress of your researches on the plants of Mexico ¶  for Godman's &amp; Salvin's Biologia Centrali-Americana you could favor me with not...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">81.10.03a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Hemsley</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Letters to W. B. Hemsley, vol. 2 (Moo-Zah), ff. 7-8.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">3/10/81</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Allow me to ask you, dear Mr Hemsley, whether in the progress of your researches on the plants of Mexico<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hemsley (1879-88).</p>
               </note> for Godman's &amp; Salvin's Biologia Centrali-Americana you could favor me with notes on the species of Pines, Oaks &amp; other trees, which yield the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">timber largely in local use</hi>
               </seg> in Mexico, also with short information on the source of the best tan-bark of Mexico. I wish very much to have this information for the soon intended new edition of my work on “select plants for industrial culture”.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B84.13.22 includes references to several additional Mexican oaks.</p>
               </note> Doubtless you have several scientific correspondents in Central America, which could give us an insight into these important technologic matters from a scientific point of view. Their and your help will be fully acknowledged in my work.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Is it really <name key="Quercus%20magnolifolia">Quercus magnolifolia</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Q. magnoliifolia</seg>? M used Q. magnolifolia in editions of his 'Select plants…'.</p>
               </note> on which the native Silkworm of Mexico spins its cocoons?<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Is it really ... cocoons <seg style="font-style: italic; ">is written on a separate folio (f. 8) of the MS.</seg>
                  </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In B84.13.22 and later editions, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Quercus%20magnolifolia">Quercus magnolifolia</name>
                     </seg> is given as the tree on which these silkworms feed, but the information is attributed to Née (presumably referring to Née (1801), p. 269).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Quercus%20magnolifolia">Quercus magnolifolia</name>
            </p>
